eton (in Devon, Gloucestershire, Somerset, Herefordshire, Shropshire, Leicestershire, North Yorkshire, Yorkshire, Cumberland), all named in Old English with <i>stapol</i> ‘post, pillar’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name is common in Ireland, where it has been established since medieval times in the counties of Tipperary and Kilkenny."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":41,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Stapleton was born in 1341 as the son of Richard Stapledon. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth De Aldburgh. He died before 24 October 1396, in England."},"et":{"1341–before 24 October 1396":"1341–enne 24. oktoobrit 1396","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1345–1384":"1345–1384","1375–1419":"1375–1419","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1341":"1341","1396":"1396","1384":"1384","21 December 1384":"21. detsember 1384","before 24 October 1396":"enne 24. oktoobrit 1396","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","England":"England"},"fi":{"1341–before 24 October 1396":"1341–ennen vuotta 24. lokakuuta 1396","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1345–1384":"1345–1384","1375–1419":"1375–1419","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1341":"1341","1396":"1396","1384":"1384","21 December 1384":"21. joulukuuta 1384","before 24 October 1396":"ennen vuotta 24. lokakuuta 1396","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","England":"England"},"fr":{"1341–before 24 October 1396":"1341–avant 24 octobre 1396","1341–1396":"1341–1396","1345–1384":"1345–1384","1375–1419":"1375–1419","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1341":"1341","1396":"1396","1384":"1384","21 December 1384":"21 décembre 1384","before 24 October 1396":"avant 24 octobre 1396","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Richard Stapleton est né en 1341, fils de Richard Stapledon. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Elizabeth De Aldburgh. Il est décédé avant 24 octobre 1396, à Angleterre."},"de":{"1341–before 24 October 1396":"1341–vor 24. Oktober 1396","1341–139